<dl id="n53088a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53088a">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53088a"> 88(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pedlar ~ <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53088a"><li>FW 310.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/lexma.htm#n53088a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/l39ma.htm#n53088a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53088a">MS BL 47479-168</ms> </li><li>JJA 54:257 <a name="mad6" href="../../ff/fdra/mda.htm#mad6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ma/mad6.htm#n53088a">Draft: II.3&sect;1.6</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">From the Russ the word passed into the Slavonic language is <i>variag</i> <font color="green">[78n1: The word <i>variag</i> in Modern Russian means a <mark>pedlar</mark> and bears witness to the strong commercial instincts of the Viking]</font>, into the Greek as <i>barangoi</i> &mdash; where it was often used in the restricted sense of members of the imperial guard largely recruited from this nation, &mdash; and into the Arabic as <i>varank</i>. <small> Allen Mawer, <a name="AMTV2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AMTV2"><cite title="source">The Vikings</cite></a>, (1913) 78</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
